< Text>
There are only two reasons you will shop here. 1. You live around here and and want to drive down the mountain for food. Or 2. You're camping up here and forgot to buy an item or two.
They have a deli with hot food but the cooked tri Tip has been under cooked 2/2 times so beware.
They have a decent alcohol and produce sections and decent overall selection.
The prices however are higher than Fresno, as expected.< /Text>

< text>
Great small town grocery store. They have everything you need and the prices are not outrageous. They make amazingly delicious sandwiches and soup.  There is also an absolutely wonderful deli case with homemade salads and fresh cold cuts and cheese. They have a nice hot food counter with great fried chicken, Jojo potatoes,    fried burritos and more. They also have a fantastic beer, wine and liquor department It's a wonderful stop on your way to Shaver Lake.<//text>

<Name>HoshiAM<//Name>< UserId.>
116347238995749830053</UserId.>
< Review>
Why walk when you can ride a golf cart. It is really helpful to rent a golf cart to see the main points of Catalina Island. I was only in Catalina Island for the day and the golf cart saves time to be able to do other activities. You can see all the main points via the route they recommend in one hour. However, it is better to rent it for the full 2 hours in case you want to see the Wrigley Memorial & Botanical Gardens.

The price for 2 hours is $90.00 and there is a $45 cash (only) deposit fee. You get the deposit back once the cart is returned. The driver who gave me the golf cart was friendly to show how to operate it. My recommendation is to make sure to reserve a time frame online. The golf carts sell out quickly when you arrive to the island. The company provides a map that shows the streets and route to take to get the best views.< /Review>

<review>(Translated by Google) In February, There was only choice of riding a golf cart because the weather was cold and there was not much to do with my daughters. 4 person cart pays $ 45 per hour, For 6 person, it costs $ 65, but the same amount must be deposited by cash. The deposit will be returned when the cart is returned. You must bring your driver's license and driving a cart was not difficult, but brakes and accelerator pedals must be deeply handled. It took about an hour to go around a given course and there was plenty of time to take pictures from the top.

Catalina, who came in February, rode a golf cart because the weather was cold and there was not much to do with young children. Four-person is $ 45 per hour, six-person is $ 65 and can be paid by card, but the same amount of deposit must be paid in cash. The deposit will be returned when the cart is returned. You must bring your driver's license and drive the card is not difficult, but brakes and accelerator pedals must be deep. It takes about an hour to go around a given course, and there is plenty of room to take pictures from the top.

(Original)
In February, There was only choice of riding a golf cart because the weather was cold and there was not much to do with my daughters. 4 person cart pays $ 45 per hour, For 6 person, it costs $65, but the same amount must be deposited by cash. The deposit will be returned when the cart is returned. You must bring your driver's license and driving a cart was not difficult, but brakes and accelerator pedals must be deeply handled. It took about an hour to go around a given course and there was plenty of time to take pictures from the top.

< user_name>
Brenda Avilla-Kintz</user_name>
<Time>1398203827111<//Time>< Review>
I had never felt the need for a storage unit until recently.  I am a full time Realtor who offers complimentary staging on my smaller sized homes that I list.  Last year, I had so many listings, that when it came time to de-stage them, my husband started to glare at me as our garage and home started to fill up.  Solution...Public Storage.  I looked at several storage facilities and selected this one due to it's central location ( I serve silicon valley, penninsula, and 680 corridor homes), cleanliness, safety of location, and prices.  I reserved a unit online.  When I got to the location, Ashley, the onsite manager, was very helpful in explaining the process and terms.  My first two weeks, I locked my units gate latch in the open position.  Ashley called me within a half an hour to let me know.  Every time I go to the facility, Ashley always greets me with a smile and a wave as I drive through the gate.  The whole experience is hassle free and it helps that Ashley is helpful and friendly, versus the creepy an condescending attitudes I expereinced elsewhere while shopping.  A great value and a great service in a safe, clean and central location.<//Review>

<review>The billiard halls in Sacramento have been around for a long time. Sharkeys was one of those places that was known as a shady hang out back in the 90s.

Nowadays it's a different clientele, different music, different management.  Gone are the bad crowds that used to frequent this place.

It would be nice if they updated the ambiance, arcade and the building itself, but it's still a good enough pool hall to go play a couple racks. .<//review><Pics>None< /Pics>< resp>

<gmapID>0x80dc0d6835e26c31:0xfb386556dcc97898< /gmapID><date>1623645169084</date><Resp>None</Resp>< review>
We ordered focaccia, a pesto pasta, the Marcello pizza, and tiramis√π. The dessert was good, but not amazing. The rest of the food was a religious experience. The quality, flavor, and proportions of the ingredients is outstanding, as is the care with which they're prepared and served.

The menu doesn't actually say what the Marcello is, but to try describing it, it's a somewhat deconstructed pizza, served with mostly cool ingredients that aren't baked with the bread, including mozzarella, prosciutto crudo, arugula, basil, tomatoes, shaved parmesan, and a drizzle of balsamic. It's a unique experience in itself, and should be on the "must try once in your life" list for anyone who finds that description intriguing.<//review>

Lately things have been moving forward again so we decided to have dinner here on Saturday. I phoned around 1pm and spoke with Sarah who reserved a table for us at 5pm. I really can't believe we go to dinner so early these days because we never eat before 6pm at home but it gets way way busy from 5pm on at this very popular eatery. In fact after we parked our wheels just a few hundred feet from the restaurant and walked towards it we could see heaps of people waiting outside for a table. It's that good ! The very second we arrived at the hostess desk at 5pm lovely hostess Benedetta escorted us to a table on the covered side patio which was already packed out. Soon after we sat down Marco the new manager came by to welcome us. We spotted Vittorio one of our fav servers and very soon he was looking after us. Fresh baked Artisan Bread & Olive Oil plus Balsamic Vinegar to dip arrived at our table. And then 2 tall glasses of Sparkling Rose materialized in front of us. My wife spotted something she favored on the Specials of the Day menu....Gnocchi - White Beef Ragu with Artichokes on Top. Okay we will share that I said plus a Giuseppe Gourmet Pizza - no sauce......Mozzarella, Porcini, Spicy Salami, Calabrese, Baby Arugula and shaved Parmigiano. My wife agreed and that is exactly what we ordered when Vittorio returned. In the meantime I walked out the front ( put on my facial mask ) to take some pics of the folks dining on the sidewalk patio and the people waiting for a table. Within a very short time our dinner order arrived together courtesy of server Ivan ( our good mate ) and everything looked sensational. My wife tried the Gnocchi first while I tucked into a slice of the Giuseppe pizza. Totally mouth watering we both agreed. My wife doesn't drink alcohol so I was scoffing down both glasses of Sparkling Rose...quite nice too ! We had half our dinner boxed to go and ordered some dessert.....Mocha Chocolate Cake which tasted very delicate & very sweet. It was just great to enjoy dinner here again after so long. I said goodbye to the hard working pizza oven guys in the kitchen and lovely Sarah at the hostess desk. WE LOVE IT !</review></record></dataset><record>

<Text>Oh my goodness, my wife and I saw the LONG LINES out of this place for weeks on end...and now we know why. This place is AMAZING!

With delicious "homemade" authentic Italian food, superb wines, and super nice & attentive staff, it's no wonder this place is so incredibly popular. We can't say enough nice about it.

My wife and I had tried their location just outside of downtown San Diego, when we first moved here, and was THRILLED to learn they were opening a location so close to us.

Now, if you're looking for a quiet little spot for a quiet romantic evening, this is NOT the place. Correction: It's romantic, just not quiet. I mean, it's LOUD. But then, it's tiny. I wouldn't be surprised if inside it didn't seat any more than 30 or so people. But it's worth it. And come summer, the outdoor spot will be divine.

Thank you, Buona Forchetta, for such superb food and attention to detail!

Love, Dave & Tammy< /Text>< pictures>

<Gmap_id>0x80dc0d6835e26c31:0xfb386556dcc97898</Gmap_id><Resp>None< /Resp><Date>1560226456238< /Date><rate>5</rate>< Review>
Had a nice dinner to start the night. Between the two of us, we ordered a salad, pasta and pizza to try each thing and also shared a bottle of wine.
We got the octopus carpaccio salad. Thinly slice tentacles that was marinated in lemon juice over a bed of arugula and a few half slices grape tomatoes and olives.
The puttanesca pizza was topped with mozzarella, anchovies, capers and olives. It was salty but beautifully tasty.
For the pasta, I wanted the bucatini pasta with the Amatriciana sauce. The noodle is like a straw, and the tomato sauce was a bit smoky from the bacon. Very good!
We got there early because it is first come first serve. The staff work like a team. Quick friendly service. We got bread with lentils in EVOO and a bottle of water for our table. The staff all wore their uniform t-shirts all with a variety of cheeky slogans of ‚Äúfork‚Äù. The seating is tight, but comfortable. They have a unisex restroom with fun wall art. I‚Äôll definitely be back if I‚Äôm in town again.</Review>

< text>
They dont take reservations, but they allow people to come and put their name in hours in advance, and then go home, and they call them.  So basically at 5pm on a Sunday, there was one couple sitting outside waiting but they had almost a two hour wait. < Review>
We love the restaurant in South Park, so we were really happy that they came to Encinitas. We got lucky and got seats at the "bar" (which really just overlooks part of the kitchen), so we didn't have to wait. Next time, we'll ask to sit outside, as we love the outdoor seating in South Park. The bread was warm and the lentils are a nice addition. We tried some of our favorite dishes, and the calamari, artichokes, and penne bolognese did not disappoint! I got the eggplant parmesan, since they didn't have my regular gnocchi bolognese, and it was great too! Their wine selection is nice. Even though it was crazy busy, the service was good. *** We went again and tried the pizza in a jar, which was really good; the calamari never disappoints; artichokes were good. The Sofia and Margarita pizzas are great. The lasagna was good, but a bit too much meat and not enough noodles for me.< /Review>

<userid>115027286096822577705<//userid><name>Zed Star<//name>< time>
1601221438360</time>
< Rate>
5<//Rate>
< review>
MAGNIFICO ! My wife and I had dinner here last night at this newly opened Italian restaurant. From experience knowing that Buona Forchetta locations get busy we arrived around 5 pm. A young lady greeted us at the entrance and showed us to a table in the side courtyard. It was packed out inside and half full on the patio already. A server fetched us a couple of glasses of water as we settled down to peruse the menu.I ordered the house IPA which the effervescent manager Giuseppe hand delivered to our table. A server named Liz brought us a free appetizer of fresh bread & marinated vegetable topping. We had been here 5 minutes and were feeling spoiled rotten. Our main server Luca took our dinner order for a plate of Amatriciana / Bucatini pasta & the Barbara white pizza. Giuseppe the manager came by to say hello again and check on us. In the twinkling of an eye our meals arrived at our table. Friendly server Liz popped by to grate fresh parmigiana on both our meals. And of course I added some chili flakes to my half of the fabulous looking pizza. The pasta tasted so perfect and the sauce just a tad spicy. The pizza was exactly as we used to at Buona Forchetta restaurants....a little crusty around the edge and soft near the center with that beautiful Italian flavor. We ate everything in front of us. We could have fitted in some Gelato for dessert but Giuseppe informed us they didn't have the gelato yet.....we understood as they only opened 5 days ago. We had been chatting all evening with the friendly couple at the next table...Tony & Rachel and really had a sensational evening. Sadly it was time to go and there was a throng of people on the sidewalk waiting to grab our table. We paid the bill and said goodbye to our mate Giuseppe. We will tell our friends and can't wait to come back !< /review>

Our main server Emiliano introduced himself and looked after us like royalty the whole time we were there. We ordered a couple of hot lattes while we thought about our lunch choice. This is, absolutely, the most terrible Sushi place I have EVER been to. First off, the "hostess" just handed me a piece of paper with the names of the rolls on it. I understand that most rolls are the same wherever you go, but THEY HAD MENUS, she just didn't give me one. Second, I didn't even get my water until AFTER my roll had come out. The guy that worked behind the bar (maybe the owner) was so completely rude. It was shocking. I was asking questions about the different rolls and he was so mean to me about it. My co-worker and I both ordered a California roll, and then we ordered a Dynamite roll to share. The California roll was fine, but when we got the Dynamite, we were both in disgust. It was not a roll whatsoever. It was literally a pile of mush on a plate covered with foil, with cheese baked on top. It was not a roll at all. When we asked the guy about it, he got MAD. Um, excuse me? It's a Dynamite ROLL that we ordered not a pile of fish thrown in a toaster. He immediately told the hostess to go get our checks. The man literally kicked us out of the place, for being unsatisfied. I still can't believe how rude he was. That is no way to run a business. Not one that's going to make it, anyway. And to top it off, the place was filthy, the walls and counters were dirty, it was awful.
I went out of my comfort zone, and decided to try something else (other than Loveboat sushi in San Marcos - BEST EVER) and I will NEVER and I repeat NEVER go there again.</review>

<Text>Like its name suggests, Alta Plaza Park is pretty high up on a small hill with four levels of stairs leading up to its central plateau , where you will be rewarded with a sweeping view of the southern part of the city that I think matches the one of Alamo Square but much less touristy. There are a playground (at the hill top!), two tennis courts, and plenty benches and spots for picnic. And obviously the park is an excellent place for stair exercises and even hill training for runners.
The structure of the park has a simple beauty,  very easy to orient yourself and walk around. All in all, this is one of the better city parks in SF.< /Text></record></dataset><record>
< GmapID>
0x808580cf24842f9d:0xffb0154102337e61<//GmapID>
< text>
Beautiful spot, panoramic views of the city. Ample benches dotted around, perfect for lunching or just chilling. The benches are long and clean, so they're great for socially distanced hanging out! Walking up can be a bit steep for someone with mobility challenges, but generally easy access for most, including strollers as the paths are wide and mostly smooth. A playground on the top and some tennis courts. It's quiet, with occasional picnic-ers on sunny days. South-facing side can get windy some days, but the west facing side is a bit more sheltered from the wind. Fillmore food stretch is just a block away, so I love to grab a sandwich and eat in the sun at the park at lunch. Kid and dog friendly, but mind the slopes - I see many balls make a break for it!</text>

<Gmap_id>0x808580cf24842f9d:0xffb0154102337e61< /Gmap_id>< Review>
Alta Plaza Park has a spectacular view of surrounding SF neighborhoods. I often come here to vent and be myself, but also to write report and submit them. Little ones will probably spend the whole day here. Warmer weather you'll see people laying on the grass and soaking it in. Good for family outing on any given day except for rain. Be careful walking on hilly grass areas, they're slippery. Next time you see a Audi S5 with a guy in it, that may very well be me. Fun times, fun times.</Review>

Currently under construction (July 2018), but the kids playground is good and it's a nice place to wall your dog as well.

It is just east enough that you're not sopped up in fog all the time.

<review>Nice park with great views of the city. It doesn't have a huge grassy area, but it's still decent. It also has a good playground for kids.

One of the most important events that goes on here is PUG SUNDAY! It's the first Sunday of every month at 2:30pm, and it's a great place to bring your pug if you have one, or just watch them chase each other if you don't.

Alta Plaza is also a nice, not crowded place to watch the fireworks on the 4th of July, if you don't mind getting the lower part of some fireworks cut off.<//review>< rating>

< Text>
I love this park for 3 reasons: 1) Views - the most gorgeous views of the city. 2) Children's Playground - my son loves the play structures, the slides, and the sandbox. There are multiple structures that can appeal to different age groups and most of the equipment are in good shape. 3) Dog Park - my son looooooves dogs but I'm not in the position to have a pet right now. Solution? I take him to Alta Plaza as there are tons of fun dogs and very friendly owners. Almost everyone allows us to pet their dogs. I didn't give it 5 stars because it can be hard to find parking. If you're within walking distance though, I totally recommend stopping by this park!<//Text>
